📢Reminder- beginning today, May 11, through May 22 you may drop your Pre-K & Kindergarten registration packets off at your child’s school between 8:00-3:00. If it’s after 3:00, please contact the school first to verify someone is there to receive your information.

Pre-K is not hard zoned, so you may apply at any school in the district. For specific questions regarding Pre-K, please contact your child’s school or scroll back and review past posts, as you may find the answer to your question there.

Kindergarten packets must be dropped off at your child’s zoned school. Even if you plan on completing an out of zone request, you must register your child at his/her zoned school first. Find your zoned school here: https://www.google.com/maps/d/viewer?mid=1SXDm3Otm7KZ3z5pGCqR6PaCH2fY&ll=35.96445614721888%2C-84.98004494999998&z=11

Attached is the link to the second packet for students in K-8 for April 27-May 8. Starting Monday 4/27 you may pick up a printed packet for free at our local Staples.

HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS/PARENTS:
☑️If you would like to pick up a high school packet from Staples, please CALL 931-707-0533 first and give them your name, school, your teacher’s first/last name and the name of the class.
☑️Calling ahead will cut down on your wait time drastically as well as help Staples get an idea of how many packets need to be printed. High school packet 1 will still be available. Since some high school teachers did a larger packet 1, they did not submit a new one for packet 2.

K-8 STUDENTS/PARENTS:
☑️K-8 students- They have several new #2 packets already printed for you to grab and go, so there is no need to call ahead.

Thank you SO much, Crossville Staples! ♥️ #StaplesConnectCrossville

post_text: This is Director of Schools, Janet Graham. Out of respect for the request from our Governor and Commissioner of Education, I am announcing that Cumberland County Schools will remain closed for the remainder of this 2019-2020 school year. This is a decision that weighs heavily on the heart of educators and we know there will be significant implications as a result of this extended closure. Our administrative team will be hard at work in planning for the closing of a school year in a truly non-traditional way. We have begun discussion about how to honor our seniors, move forward with summer school planning in the event we can have it and how we will begin a new year following this lengthy closure. Many decisions need to be made to care for our children. Know that we have children at the forefront of every decision to be made. We will be updating you often and ask for your cooperation and patience as we develop plans to provide educational opportunities for our children.

Happy National Book Lovers Day 📚📕

"National Book Lovers Day on August 9th harnesses all the excitement bibliophiles feel about books into one celebration.

A day for all those who love to read, National Book Lovers Day encourages you to find your favorite reading place, a good book (whether it be fiction or non-fiction) and read the day away.

Bibliophile – a person who has a great appreciation for or collects books.

Sit back, relax and READ!"

-National Day Calendar 2019

post_text: We would like to take this time to clarify some misconceptions regarding the SnowBird text alert. Prior to this year, Remind (the texting service we have been using) has been FREE. Beginning this school year, Remind is now requiring a user fee for groups larger than 150 people. This fee will exceed $20,000 to keep the texting service just for students. This does not include additional fees for parents, guardians, relatives, community members, etc. Parents and/or Guardians will still receive an automated phone call from the Cumberland County School District when school has been delayed or canceled. We apologize for any confusion.

post_text: Today (9-14-18) at approximately 2:30 pm, there was a shooting involving 3 individuals that occurred at the Cumberland County Schools Bus Garage. It was determined that the threat was contained at the scene therefore no schools were considered to be at risk. Due to the timing of this event, our primary concern was that all of our students were transported safely and as promptly as possible. Several buses were unable to leave the garage as a result of this event, which created some challenges. However, all students that were transported were home by approximately 5:30 pm.
